# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1951-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1951-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1951-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1951-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1951-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1951-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1951-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1951-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1951-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1951-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1951-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1951-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1951-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1951-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The **1951 World Series** matched the two-time defending champion New York Yankees against the New York Giants, who had won the National League pennant in a thrilling three-game playoff with the Brooklyn Dodgers on the legendary home run by Bobby Thomson (the Shot Heard 'Round the World).
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the Series, the Yankees showed some power of their own, including Gil McDougald's grand slam home run in Game 5, at the Polo Grounds.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Yankees won the Series in six games, for their third straight title and 14th overall.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] This would be the last World Series for Joe DiMaggio, who retired afterward, and the first for rookies Willie Mays and Mickey Mantle.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] This was the last Subway Series the Giants played in.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Both teams would meet again eleven years later after the Giants relocated to San Francisco.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] They have not played a World Series against each other since.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] This was the first World Series announced by Bob Sheppard, who was in his first year as Yankee Stadium's public address announcer.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be televised exclusively by one network (NBC) as well as the first to be televised nationwide, as coaxial cable had recently linked both coasts.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] This World Series also matched up two of baseball's most colorful managers, Casey Stengel of the Yankees and Leo Durocher of the Giants.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] This was the 13th appearance by the Giants in Series play, their ninth loss, and their first appearance since the 1937 World Series.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Mantle's bad luck with injuries in the Major Leagues began here.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the fifth inning of Game 2 at Yankee Stadium, Mays flied to deep right center.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] DiMaggio and Mantle converged on the ball, DiMaggio called Mantle off, and Mantle stutter-stepped, catching a cleat in a drain cover, and fell to the ground in a heap with a wrenched knee as DiMaggio made the catch.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Mantle was done for this Series, but would come back to play many more.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] New York City became the first city to host an NBA Finals and a World Series in the same calendar year.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Monte Irvin's daring baserunning got the Giants off to a fast start in this New York – New York series.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] He singled in the first inning, sped to third on Whitey Lockman's RBI single, then stole home off Yankee starter Allie Reynolds.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Yankees cut the Giants' lead to 2–1 in the second when Gil McDougald doubled with one out off Dave Koslo and scored on Jerry Coleman's single.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The scored remained that way until the sixth when Alvin Dark's three-run home run gave the Giants a commanding 5–1 lead.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Koslo pitched a complete game to give the Giants a 1–0 series lead.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The first three batters Larry Jansen faced were Mickey Mantle, Phil Rizzuto and Gil McDougald, all of whom singled for a quick 1-0 Yankee lead.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] It could have been worse, but the next batter Joe DiMaggio bounced into a 6-4-3 double play and Yogi Berra struck out.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The next inning, Joe Collins's home run extended the Yankees' lead to 2–0.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the fifth Willie Mays flied out to Joe DiMaggio, who waved off right fielder Mantle, who got his spikes caught in an exposed drain and injured his knee and had to leave the game.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] This injury would stick with him for the rest of his career.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Monte Irvin scored in the seventh, tagging and coming home on pinch-hitter Bill Rigney's bases-loaded sacrifice fly, as the Giants got within 2–1.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] But winning pitcher Eddie Lopat, who pitched a complete game, helped himself to an insurance run with an RBI single in the eighth after Bobby Brown hit a leadoff single and moved to second on a groundout off George Spencer.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Yankees' 3–1 win tied the series shifting to the Polo Grounds.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Giants struck first in Game 3 when Bobby Thomson hit a leadoff double and scored on Willie Mays' single in the second, then a five-run fifth inning was the undoing of Yankee starter Vic Raschi.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Eddie Stanky walked with one out, moved to third on an error, and scored on Al Dark's single.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] After a Hank Thompson single, another error on Monte Irvin's fielder's choice allowed another run to score and put two on, then a Whitey Lockman three-run home run gave Giants starter Jim Hearn a comfortable 6–0 lead.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the eighth on a bases-loaded walk to Joe Collins, then in the ninth on Gene Woodling's home run off Sheldon Jones, who retired the next two batters to end the game and give the Giants a 2–1 series lead.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the rain-delayed Game 4, the Giants again scored first when Al Dark doubled with one out in the opening inning off Allie Reynolds and scored on Monte Irvin's single, but the Yankees tied the game in the second on Joe Collins's RBI single with two on off Sal Maglie.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] After a single and walk, Reynolds's RBI single in the fourth put the Yankees up 2–1.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Joe DiMaggio's first home run of the Series (and the last of his career) following a Yogi Berra single in the fifth extended their lead to 4–1.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the seventh, reliever Sheldon Jones allowed a single and walk, then an error on a pickoff attempt allowed one run to score before Gil McDougald's RBI single made it 6–1 Yankees.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Reynolds allowed a one-out RBI single to Bobby Thomson in the ninth before getting Willie Mays to hit into the game-ending double play as the Yankees tied the series with a 6–2 win.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] After two one-out walks in the third, Joe DiMaggio's RBI single tied the game, then after an intentional walk loaded the bases, Gil McDougald's grand slam off Jansen put the Yankees up 5–1.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Next inning, Phil Rizzuto's home run off Kennedy after a walk extended their lead to 7–1.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the sixth, Rizzuto singled off Spencer before Yogi Berra's single and Johnny Mize's double scored a run each, making it 9–1 Yankees.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] In the seventh, a bases-loaded walk to Rizzuto forced in a run, then Al Corwin threw a wild pitch that let another run score before DiMaggio's two-run double capped the game's scoring at 13–1 Yankees, who were a win away from the World Series championship as the series returned to Yankee Stadium.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Yankees struck first in Game 6 on Gil McDougald's bases-loaded sacrifice fly in the first off Dave Koslo.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The Giants tied the game in the fifth off Vic Raschi when Willie Mays hit a leadoff single, moved two bases on a wild pitch and sacrifice fly, and scored on Eddie Stanky's sacrifice fly.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Playing right field in place of Mickey Mantle, Hank Bauer benefited from a tricky Yankee Stadium wind—as well as the umpire's generous call of a ball on Dave Koslo's two-strike pitch—to belt a bases-loaded triple in the sixth inning that would be the difference.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Bauer also ensured that the lead held up.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Trailing 4–1 in the ninth, the Giants loaded the bases with no outs on three singles off Johnny Sain.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Enter reliever Bob Kuzava, acquired in June from the Washington Senators.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] After two sacrifice flies and the score now 4–3, pinch hitter Sal Yvars hit a sinking liner to right.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] The stadium crowd gasped as Bauer momentarily lost the ball in the crowd's white shirts and the shadows.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] But he located it again and charged forward.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Bauer, who played in nine World Series and always came through when it mattered most, slid on his knees to catch the ball inches off the ground to end the game and the 1951 World Series.
[src:1951-world-series/1951-world-series] Game 6 was the last baseball game ever played by Joe DiMaggio.
[src:1951-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1951-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
